<h2>Reorderable List</h2>
<p>A list whose <strong>item order is user-mutable</strong> — by pointer drag and, equally, by keyboard. It relocates items with the atomic <code>Element.moveBefore()</code> so a moved card keeps its focus, in-flight animations, iframes, and custom-element connection state instead of being torn down and rebuilt. This is the <em>reorder</em> half of "drag and drop"; moving a payload (item or file) into a zone that validates what it accepts is a separate, data-transfer concern (<a href="/backlog/007-gap-11-clipboard-dnd-files-intents/">backlog #007</a>).</p>

<p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
  <strong>Terminology:</strong> See <a href="/semantics/">Semantics &amp; Glossary</a> for <a href="/semantics/#term-reorder">Reorder</a>, <a href="/semantics/#term-reorderable-list">Reorderable List</a>, <a href="/semantics/#term-drag-handle">Drag Handle</a>, <a href="/semantics/#term-keyboard-reorder">Keyboard Reorder</a>, and <a href="/semantics/#term-reorder-commit-strategy">Reorder Commit Strategy</a>.
</p>

<p><strong>Manual order, not computed sort.</strong> Reorder produces a hand-set order; the <a href="/intents/collection-operations/"><code>sort</code> dimension of Collection Operations</a> produces a comparator-computed order. A list is one or the other, never both at once — they are distinct answers to "what determines order" and cross-reference rather than merge.</p>

<h3>Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Pointer_events">Pointer Events</a></td><td>Baseline</td><td>The default drag path — unifies mouse/touch/pen, captured for the duration of a drag. Preferred over HTML5 DnD for in-list reorder (better touch &amp; a11y)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Element/moveBefore">Element.moveBefore()</a></td><td>Baseline 2025 (progressive)</td><td>Atomic relocation that preserves item state; wired via the <a href="/blocks/component/">Component</a> block's <code>preserve-on-move</code>, with an <code>insertBefore</code> fallback</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/">WAI-ARIA APG</a></td><td>Authoring Practices</td><td>Keyboard-operable drag + polite live-region announcement; the deprecated <code>aria-grabbed</code>/<code>aria-dropeffect</code> are <strong>not</strong> used</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTML_Drag_and_Drop_API">HTML Drag and Drop API</a></td><td>Baseline</td><td>Reserved for cross-window / OS file transfer (data-transfer, <a href="/backlog/007-gap-11-clipboard-dnd-files-intents/">#007</a>) — not the in-list reorder default</td></tr>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h3>Framework Research</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
  <tr><th>Source</th><th>Key Patterns Adopted</th></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://dndkit.com/">dnd-kit</a></td><td>Pointer / keyboard / touch as peer <em>sensors</em> — keyboard is a first-class sensor, not a bolt-on</td></tr>
  <tr><td><a href="https://sortablejs.github.io/Sortable/">SortableJS</a></td><td><code>handle</code> (scoped grab), cross-list groups, <code>onEnd</code> commit hook</td></tr>
